<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Wrath of Chung: Connie Chung got a little miffed Saturday when the tables 
were turned and she was barraged with questions about the glitz factor of her 
newly redone interview show on CBS. "You people are so insulting," she told a 
roomful of television critics at the Century Plaza. 
</P>
<P>
The reporters were grilling her about the news value of "Face to Face With 
Connie Chung," formerly "Saturday Night With Connie Chung," which moves with 
its new name to Mondays at 10 p.m. next Monday. Chung insisted that celebrity 
interviews were not the driving force of her hourlong program, despite recent 
network promotions that highlight the star-side chats. "Look, it's a magazine 
program," Chung said, her voice rising. "We're going to have all kinds of 
stories." GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
