<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN COURT: A SUMMARY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA-RELATED BUSINESS LITIGATION 
DEVELOPMENTS DURING THE PAST WEEK. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Big Rock Mesa Landslides: Fireman's Fund Insurance Co. was sued by five 
insurance companies seeking to recover the costs of defending lawsuits filed by 
Malibu homeowners over the Big Rock Mesa landslides. The Los Angeles Superior 
Court suit says Fireman's Fund and the plaintiff-insurers provided insurance to 
some of the homeowners. 
</P>
<P>
When the owners were cross-sued by several government entities, the suit says, 
Fireman's Fund named a single law firm to defend them but refused to pay for 
individual lawyers for each homeowner. To avoid potential conflicts, the five 
plaintiffs paid for separate attorneys to defend the homeowners and now want 
Fireman's Fund to reimburse them for the proportionate share of the costs. The 
Big Rock Mesa litigation was settled for more than $100 million last year. 
(Filed July 9, 1990. Case No. BC005297) 
</P>
</TEXT>
