2066 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRIAL TO FOCUS ON ISSUE OF SUBLIMINAL MESSAGES IN ROCK; 
</P>
<P>
LAWSUIT: PARENTS CHARGE A JUDAS PRIEST RECORDING WITH AN ALLEGED MESSAGE SAYING 
'DO IT' LED TO SONS' DEATHS. CBS RECORDS DENIES ANY SUCH MESSAGES EXISTED. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHUCK PHILIPS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
RENO, NEV. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We were mesmerized. There was no doubt, no second thought in my mind that I was 
going to pull that trigger, even though I didn't want to die. 
</P>
<P>
 -- James Vance 
</P>
<P>
That's how Sparks, Nev., teen-ager James Vance claimed he felt after listening 
to an album by British heavy-metal band Judas Priest the day he and a friend 
turned a gun on themselves and pulled the trigger. 
</P>
<P>
Vance's best friend, Raymond Belknap, 17, was killed by the self-inflicted 
gunshot on that Dec. 23, 1985, afternoon. Vance, 19, survived his suicide 
attempt, but was horribly disfigured and died three years later of 
complications possibly associated with the incident. 
</P>
<P>
Parents of both young men believe the rock group was responsible for the deaths 
of their sons -- and are attempting to prove it in a court trial that begins 
today in the Washoe District Court here. 
</P>
<P>
In the unprecedented case, attorneys for the parents will try to persuade the 
judge that auditory subliminal messages caused the teen-agers to shoot 
themselves. The parents are seeking unspecified money damages to compensate for 
the deaths, and to support a child fathered by Vance after the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
They are also seeking to recover money for medical bills plus punitive damages 
from CBS Records, which distributed "Stained Class," the 1978 Judas Priest 
album that the youths listened to that afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
Kenneth McKenna, co-counsel for the parents, said last week that he believes 
many rock bands presently use subliminal messages in their music and he hopes 
the Reno case will send a warning to the industry. 
</P>
<P>
"Whether we win or lose this case," McKenna said, "I hope rock bands start to 
get the message that they need to be more socially responsible." 
</P>
<P>
Suellen Fulstone, the attorney for CBS Records and Judas Priest, said the 
lawsuit may be motivated by reasons that have nothing to do with Judas Priest. 
</P>
<P>
"Although I would not presume to speak for the plaintiffs," Fulstone said, 
"this suit, like other product-liability suits, may simply be motivated by the 
possibility of recovering money." 
</P>
<P>
If the case against Judas Priest is successful it could have an impact on the 
way record companies view artistic expression, say industry observers. They 
believe it also could serve as an impetus for other families to file similar 
lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
But Washoe District Judge Jerry Whitehead, in a legal opinion last August, 
suggested that rock 'n' roll is not what is on trial in Reno but that the 
employment of auditory subliminal messages is. 
</P>
<P>
In the opinion, Whitehead, who will hear the trial, said that the court 
respected the First Amendment right of artists to express themselves, but that 
subliminal messages don't enjoy such privileges because they are aimed at the 
subconscious. 
</P>
<P>
He based his conclusion on three grounds: 
</P>
<P>
* Subliminal communication does not advance any of the purposes of free speech. 
</P>
<P>
* An individual has a First Amendment right to be free from unwanted speech. 
</P>
<P>
* The listener's right of privacy outweighs the speaker's right of free speech 
when subliminal speech is used. 
</P>
<P>
"We must . . . decide whether, under the factual circumstances of this case, 
there is a triable issue of fact as to whether the subliminal communications 
were a legal cause of the Dec. 23, 1985, shootings." 
</P>
<P>
There is general agreement among all parties regarding the events in the hours 
preceding the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
Vance and Belknap spent the afternoon in Belknap's bedroom in his parents' 
house, drinking beer, smoking pot and listening to Judas Priest music. In a 
sudden fit of violence, they started to punch and kick holes in the walls, 
destroying everything in the room but the stereo. 
</P>
<P>
The youths then picked up a 12-gauge sawed-off shotgun, jumped out the window 
and ran to the playground of a local church. Sitting on a merry-go-round, 
Belknap wedged the stock of the gun under his chin and pulled the trigger. 
Vance followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
Belknap died immediately. Vance blew the bottom of his face off, but survived, 
only to endure three years of painful reconstructive surgery before he died on 
Nov. 24, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Initially, the product-liability suit alleged that violent and suicidal themes 
present in Judas Priest's music were the causal factor in the deaths. Attorneys 
for the mothers of both teen-agers -- Aunetta Roberson and Phyllis Vance -- 
filed law suits against Judas Priest and CBS Records, the band's record 
company, in 1986. During the next year and a half, Vance cited specific lyrics 
from the song "Beyond the Realms of Death" as a motivating factor in the 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
But by October, 1988, the parents' attorneys amended their original complaint, 
alleging that specific subliminal messages -- saying "Do it. Do it. . . . " -- 
had been implanted in a different Judas Priest song, "Better by You, Better 
Than Me," and that those messages, in tandem with the record's overt violent 
and suicidal imagery, precipitated the suicide attempt. (See related article on 
Page 11.) 
</P>
<P>
They also allege that the album contains at least two lines of lyrics that when 
played backward reveal satanic messages. 
</P>
<P>
Judas Priest vocalist Robert Halford denies that the band's music has ever 
sought to glorify suicide or satanism. 
</P>
<P>
"I've always believed that everything that Judas Priest has done will have a 
positive effect because of what we give to people through our music," Halford 
said in a 1988 court deposition. "My personal belief and opinion about this 
band from 1971 onwards is that everything we have done has been for the good." 
</P>
<P>
Subliminal messages are comparable to post-hypnotic suggestions, experts say, 
and have reportedly been used in advertising campaigns since the mid-'50s. 
</P>
<P>
The theory behind visual subliminal imagery, experts also maintain, is that 
while subliminal images may flash before the viewer at a very rapid speed, they 
can be detected by the human eye and registered in the brain. 
</P>
<P>
But according to Anthony Pellicano, a forensic audio specialist who will 
testify for CBS Records, the volume at which alleged auditory subliminal sounds 
are produced is not loud enough to cause the eardrum to vibrate. If the eardrum 
does not vibrate, he says, then the message cannot be sent to the brain. 
</P>
<P>
Fulstone, the Reno attorney representing CBS and the band, denies the existence 
of any subliminal content or backward sounds on the Judas Priest album. 
</P>
<P>
"The subliminal argument is all invention. It has absolutely no basis in fact," 
Fulstone said. "It is simply a vehicle for the plaintiffs to pursue a case that 
is otherwise marred by the First Amendment." 
</P>
<P>
Fulstone suggested that the suicide attempts had nothing to do with Judas 
Priest's music, but were prompted by a variety of social and psychological 
problems that had haunted the youths from childhood. 
</P>
<P>
She pointed to a history of crime, domestic violence and substance abuse in 
both of the youths' backgrounds, detailed in Whitehead's legal opinion. 
</P>
<P>
In the opinion, Whitehead said that Vance and Belknap were both violent 
individuals who had experienced academic and disciplinary problems. Among the 
drugs they used were LSD, speed, cocaine, marijuana and alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
Court records also reveal that both youths were physically abused by their 
parents as children, dropped out of school after the 10th grade and drifted 
from job to job. 
</P>
<P>
"I do believe that it is a natural response for families who are experiencing 
genuine grief over the loss of a loved one to deal with those feelings by 
looking for someone to blame," Fulstone said. 
</P>
<P>
Responded McKenna, "Let me answer with a story. If you have a pretty young 
daughter and you tell her 20 times, 'Don't walk down the alley behind your 
house, it's dangerous.' You warn her, 'Don't wear a short dress.' And you say, 
'Don't talk to or take candy from strangers.' 
</P>
<P>
"Then one day she walks down that alley in a short dress and she takes candy 
from a freak who violates her, cuts her throat and kills her. She is obviously 
at fault. She disobeyed everything you told her to do. But who would you be 
angry at? 
</P>
<P>
"Is the freak a factor in the homicide? You bet he is. In this case, CBS is the 
freak." 
</P>
<P>
To persuade the court that subliminal messages could have led the two Reno 
teen-agers to shoot themselves, attorneys for the parents must first 
demonstrate that such messages actually exist on the Judas Priest album. 
</P>
<P>
McKenna and his co-counsel Timothy Post said they are prepared to do so through 
the use of a computer program that can detect such messages. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the attorneys will present testimony by Wilson Bryan Key, an 
author and lecturer who maintains that CBS employed subliminals in Judas 
Priest's music to increase the marketability of their albums. 
</P>
<P>
"The deaths of James Vance and Ray Belknap provide us with a textbook example 
of how subliminal messages surface in human behavior," said Key, who has 
consulted on nearly two dozen cases involving homicide, suicide and acts of 
violence. "As far as I'm concerned, this is just another example of corporate 
willingness to do anything they can to make a buck." 
</P>
<P>
Pellicano, the Los Angeles forensic audio specialist who will testify for CBS 
Records, maintained that there is no subliminal content or backward sounds 
anywhere on the recording. 
</P>
<P>
"The theory of subliminal messages advanced by the parents' attorneys borders 
on deceit and voodooism," Pellicano said. 
</P>
<P>
"For the plaintiffs to suggest that some auditory subliminal scheme is at work 
here, it implies that there was a conspiracy of evil in 1978 between Judas 
Priest, the engineers, the executives and everyone at CBS involved in the 
production to create an album that would cause young people to kill themselves. 
Does that sound credible to you?" 
</P>
<P>
The trial is expected to last from three to six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
CHRONOLOGY OF JUDAS PRIEST CASEThese are the steps that led to the Judas Priest 
trial: 
</P>
<P>
Dec. 23, 1985: Raymond Belknap, 17, and James Vance, 19, each attempted to 
commit suicide with a shotgun. Belknap died immediately, but Vance survived the 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
Dec. 24: Vance indicated to police that he attempted suicide because "life 
sucks." He did not blame Judas Priest. 
</P>
<P>
Jan. 12, 1986: The father of John McCollum, a 19-year-old California youth who 
killed himself in 1984 after listening to a recording by Ozzy Osbourne, 
announced his intent to sue Osbourne and CBS Records over his son's death. 
Vance's mother read media accounts of the Osbourne suit, according to court 
records. 
</P>
<P>
February: Aunetta Roberson (Belknap's mother) contacted attorney Kenneth 
McKenna and asked him to file a lawsuit against Judas Priest and CBS Records, 
McKenna said. McKenna then contacted the Vance family to see if they would be 
interested in joining the suit, but Phyllis Vance declined, according to court 
records. In the same month, McKenna called the attorney that filed the Osbourne 
suit and received copies of legal papers relating to the McCollum case. 
</P>
<P>
March: Vance told police in that the suicidal themes in Judas Priest's music 
might have caused the shootings. 
</P>
<P>
April: Vance wrote a letter to Belknap's mother saying that the Judas Priest 
album "mesmerized" both youths into believing the "answer to life was death." 
</P>
<P>
May 8: McKenna filed a lawsuit against Judas Priest and CBS Records on behalf 
of Roberson. 
</P>
<P>
July 10: A separate suit was filed on behalf of the Vance family. The cases 
were consolidated Dec. 3, 1986. 
</P>
<P>
Attorneys for the parents asked CBS to turn over the 24-track master recording 
of Judas Priest's "Stained Class" album for analysis. McKenna said that CBS 
told him that the master recordings were lost. The company did deliver a master 
copy of one song on the album entitled "Better by You, Better Than Me." 
</P>
<P>
July 12, 1988: The California District Court of Appeals ruled that Osbourne's 
music is protected by the First Amendment and dismissed the McCollum suit. 
</P>
<P>
October, 1988: A Sacramento audio engineer allegedly detected "subliminal" 
messages on the Judas Priest song. The families then alleged that these 
subliminal messages precipitated the suicide attempt. 
</P>
<P>
Nov. 15: James Vance was admitted to the psychiatric unit of the Washoe Medical 
Center; he died Nov. 24 of heart failure. 
</P>
<P>
Aug. 23, 1989: Washoe District Judge Jerry Whitehood ruled that subliminal 
messages are not protected by the First Amendment and recommended the case be 
tried before a jury. 
</P>
<P>
July 9, 1990: Whitehead accepted an agreement between both sides in the case to 
waive a jury trial.CHUCK PHILIPS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Teen-agers Raymond Belknap, left, and James Vance. ; Photo, Attorneys 
Kenneth McKenna, left, and Tim Post, in McKenna's Reno office, represent 
parents of teen-agers who shot themselves. BRUCE BENNETT / Los Angeles Times; 
Photo, The British heavy metal band Judas Priest is under attack for the 
alleged subliminal content on its 1978 album, "Stained Class." 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
