<P>
887 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO FUNDS, MUCH FURY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAN BRESLAUER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Donna Reed she's not. But Holly Hughes, that frisky femme of the performance 
world and author of plays whose titles you can't print in this newspaper, is 
cooking plenty. 
</P>
<P>
With her poet's ear tuned to the ironies of gay life, her life, and the 
ins-and-outs of waiting tables, Hughes is on the road to set some records 
straight. 
</P>
<P>
The New Yorker is one of four performance artists who were recently recommended 
for NEA support by a peer panel of theater experts and then denied that funding 
in an unprecedented action by NEA Chairman John E. Frohnmayer. 
</P>
<P>
Despite these trying times, Hughes -- a Grove Press-published playwright, 
Jerome Foundation grantee and recipient of a MacDowell Fellowship -- refuses to 
let what she sees as the "open season on artists, whether they're publicly 
funded or not," stop her from making art. 
</P>
<P>
The world premiere of her performance "Dead Meat" ("I didn't know how prophetic 
my title would be," she quips. "I didn't plan to live up to it this way") comes 
to Highways on Tuesday for a benefit performance. The run continues Thursday as 
part of "Ecce Lesbo/Ecce Homo," Highways' second annual gay and lesbian 
performance festival. Later this month, Hughes reprises her solo, "World 
Without End." 
</P>
<P>
Tired from repeated sessions with the press and legal counsel, Hughes spoke 
about the Frohnmayer action from Seattle, where she was taking part in the 
National Gay and Lesbian Theater Festival. (Frohnmayer declined comment for 
this article.) 
</P>
<P>
"I'm furious," says Hughes. "All four of us are appealing the decision. Not 
only did we get our grants turned down, but before the overturnings were 
announced, (John) Fleck, Karen (Finley) and I were getting our careers 
demolished by misrepresentation in the press." 
</P>
<P>
Hughes has been recommended for three NEA grants in different categories during 
the last three months. Before last year, when Congress installed a clause that 
requires grantees to sign a pledge to comply with restrictive language in the 
NEA's appropriations bill, Hughes was awarded a 1989 Inter-arts grant. 
</P>
<P>
In March, after the new language was in place, she won a 1990 playwriting 
grant. "I smeared the word lesbian all over my application," says Hughes. "I 
wanted to make it perfectly clear; I have yet to receive that money." 
</P>
<P>
After that award, says Hughes, the situation got much worse. "It was leaked to 
me in the spring that I'd been recommended for funding in the solo 
performance-artist category," she says, "but the solo fellowships had been 
deferred. 
</P>
<P>
"There was a gag order, but obviously somebody in the NEA was talking and 
misrepresenting the work," recalls Hughes. "I contacted Frohnmayer's office in 
early June when these distortions first started coming out in the Washington 
Times and said, 'What are you going to do about these leaks?' 
</P>
<P>
"I hadn't committed any crime other than applying to the NEA," says Hughes. "I 
was offered all sorts of assurances that (Frohnmayer) was concerned and wanted 
to protect the artists." 
</P>
<P>
Yet, says Hughes, those promises apparently didn't matter next to what she 
describes as Frohnmayer's desire "to make sacrifices to the right wing. 
</P>
<P>
"I suspect the one thing that politicians do all the time is leak something and 
see what the public response to it is," she says. "It's not impossible that 
these leaks were coming from Frohnmayer's office." 
</P>
<P>
"I have this fantasy: 'A Day in the Life of John Frohnmayer.' He wakes up in 
the morning and crawls on his belly to the door of (North Carolina Sen.) Jesse 
Helms. And he scratches on Helms' door and says, 'Ohhh, ohhhh, what can I do 
for you today? Take some more trash out of the NEA -- those lesbians, those 
feminists, those gay people -- and demolish the entire performance-art category 
and establish in its place maybe a bake-off?' " 
</P>
<P>
Kidding aside, Hughes says that Frohnmayer isn't doing his job. "Funding is 
supposed to be based on artistic merit alone," she says. "The chairman's job is 
to insulate (the process) from political realities, meaning Jesse Helms and 
(Lomita Rep.) Dana Rohrabacher." 
</P>
<P>
The reason for the four "sacrifices," says Hughes, is politics. "It diverts 
attention," she says. "It's easier to de-fund four performance artists and to 
look like you're doing something, than to indict Charles Keating or the 
President's son" (both of whom are involved in savings and loan scandals). 
</P>
<P>
"The total of all four of our grants was just $23,000, which is just a weekend 
at Kennebunkport for the Bushes -- if they don't bring Millie along." 
</P>
<P>
Nor, says Hughes, does the assault on the arts stop with the defunding of the 
four performers. "Various organizations from the NEA to city governments are 
going after spaces that present us," says Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
"The Kitchen in New York is the subject of three grueling audits from the IRA. 
The WOW Cafe is getting eviction notices. Franklin Furnace was shut down, 
ostensibly for fire reasons, but really because they presented Karen (Finley). 
And Sushi in San Diego -- which has presented all four of us -- has been 
getting hate mail and phone calls because the religious right in San Diego has 
been complaining to the city council. 
</P>
<P>
"We have to remember other repressive cultures," Hughes continues. "It always 
begins with the censorship of artists, the lack of tolerance for dissent and 
the persecution of a minority." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Performance artist Holly Hughes PAUL ERICKSON 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
