<P>
GARDEN GROVE MAN, HELD FOR DRUNKENNESS, DIES IN POLICE CELL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man who was arrested on suspicion of public drunkenness died in a holding 
cell Sunday night when he apparently choked on his own vomit, Garden Grove 
police said this morning. 
</P>
<P>
Nasr Mohamed, 42, of Garden Grove, who was taken into custody at 8:25 p.m. for 
intoxicated behavior while standing outside a supermarket at Euclid Street and 
Chapman Avenue, was pronounced dead by paramedics about 10:15 p.m., Police Sgt. 
Steve Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
After taking Mohamed into custody, police took him to the police station, and 
locked him into one of three holding cells monitored by television cameras. 
</P>
<P>
Sanders said Mohamed's body was discovered by Sgt. Dan Lyons, night watch 
commander, while he was making routine rounds of the cells. 
</P>
<P>
Police Chief John Robertson said police could not foresee Mohamed's death. He 
described the man as a "cooperative intoxicated person," who immediately "laid 
down and fell right asleep." 
</P>
<P>
Although autopsy results are not due until late this afternoon, police 
speculated that Mohamed died when he began vomiting and was unable to wake up 
fully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
